  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The Queensland Building and Construction Commission (QBCC) Home Warranty Scheme is a statutory insurance scheme that protects owners of residential property when licensed building work goes wrong. For sellers of homes that have had recent renovations, extensions, or new construction, QBCC cover is part of the property's history that buyers and their solicitors will examine, and it can affect both the buyer's confidence in the work and the legal position you carry forward after settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What QBCC home warranty insurance actually covers</h2>
      <p>The scheme covers residential building work valued at more than $3,300 carried out by a QBCC-licensed contractor. Cover is paid for by the licensed builder as part of the contract price, with the premium calculated on the value of the work, and it provides the property owner with three forms of protection.</p>

      <p>The first is non-completion cover, which protects the owner if the builder dies, becomes insolvent, or otherwise fails to complete the contracted work. The second is defects cover, which protects against defective work for a defined period after practical completion: six years and three months for structural defects and twelve months for non-structural defects. The third is subsidence cover, which addresses certain ground-related failures attributable to defective foundations.</p>

      <p>Importantly, the cover attaches to the property, not the original owner. When you sell a Brisbane home that has had QBCC-insured work in the past six years, the unexpired portion of the cover transfers to the new owner automatically. They can claim against the scheme for defects discovered after they take possession, within the remaining defects period.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why this matters when you list the property</h2>
      <p>Buyers and their solicitors increasingly ask about recent building work as part of due diligence. The questions usually take a predictable shape. Was the work done by a licensed builder. Was QBCC home warranty insurance taken out. Were council approvals obtained. Was a final certificate issued. Are records of the warranty available to be inherited.</p>

      <p>If you can answer all of those questions clearly and produce documentation, the building work becomes a feature of the home rather than a question mark. If you cannot, the buyer's solicitor may flag the work as a concern, the buyer may push for a price reduction or a special condition, and in the worst case the contract may fall over because the buyer cannot get comfortable with the unknown.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Documents to gather before listing</h2>
      <p>Pull together the building contract, the QBCC home warranty insurance certificate, council approval and final inspection certificates, and any compliance certificates for plumbing or electrical work. If the work involved a swimming pool, gather the pool safety certificate. If solar was installed, gather the installation certificate and any inverter warranty documents.</p>

      <p>If you cannot find paperwork, the QBCC online licence and case search lets you confirm whether a licensed builder carried out work at the address and whether warranty insurance was issued. The Brisbane City Council building approval search lets you check whether work had a development approval. Both are public-facing services that take a few minutes to use, and the results are exactly what a buyer's solicitor will check anyway.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Owner-builder work changes the conversation</h2>
      <p>If you carried out the building work as an owner-builder rather than engaging a licensed builder, QBCC home warranty cover does not apply, and Queensland law imposes specific disclosure obligations when you sell within six years and six months of the work being completed.</p>

      <p>Under section 47 of the Queensland Building and Construction Commission Act 1991, an owner-builder selling within that window must give the buyer a written notice in the prescribed form before the contract is signed. The notice tells the buyer that the work was performed by an owner-builder and that QBCC warranty insurance does not cover it. The notice must also be referenced in the contract. Failing to provide the notice gives the buyer a statutory right to terminate the contract before settlement and may attract a penalty.</p>

      <p>This is one of the most commonly missed disclosures in Queensland conveyancing, and it is also one of the most likely to give a buyer a clean exit if the deal turns sour for unrelated reasons. Address it through your solicitor before the property is listed, not on the day a contract is being signed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Unlicensed or unapproved work</h2>
      <p>Building work carried out by an unlicensed person, or work that should have had council approval and did not get it, is a separate problem from owner-builder work. There is no QBCC cover for unlicensed work. Buyers may inherit liability if council later requires the work to be made compliant, demolished, or certified retrospectively, and that risk transfers cleanly across at settlement unless it is disclosed and negotiated.</p>

      <p>The cleanest path is to address compliance before listing where it is practical to do so. Engaging a licensed certifier to assess the work, obtaining a building certificate from council, or in some cases applying for a regularisation approval, removes the issue from the buyer's due diligence. Where the work cannot be regularised, transparent disclosure with supporting estimates of the cost to rectify gives the buyer information to factor into their offer rather than reasons to walk away mid-contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the buyer's building and pest inspection looks for</h2>
      <p>A standard building and pest inspection at the contract stage will identify obvious recent work, particularly extensions, decks, additional rooms, and bathroom or kitchen renovations. Inspectors are trained to flag work that lacks the appearance of professional execution or that does not match the original construction in materials or method. When that happens, the inspector's report often prompts the buyer's solicitor to ask the questions covered above.</p>

      <p>Being prepared with documentation before the inspection happens shortens the conversation and avoids the back-and-forth that can erode buyer confidence. If you can hand a building and pest inspector the QBCC certificate and council approvals at the same time as access to the property, the report comes back cleaner and the buyer's path to unconditional is faster.</p>

